  "prompt": "Has Voyager-1 confirmed that there are no Planet X and Nemesis star?",
  "response": "As of October 2023, **Voyager 1** has not directly confirmed or denied the existence of **Planet X** (a hypothetical large planet beyond Neptune) or the **Nemesis star** (a hypothesized companion star to the Sun). Voyager 1's primary mission was to study the outer planets of the solar system and explore the interstellar medium, not to search for undiscovered planets or stars.\n\n### Regarding Planet X:\n- The existence of Planet X (sometimes referred to as **Planet Nine**) is still a topic of scientific debate. While some astronomers propose that gravitational anomalies in the outer solar system suggest the presence of a large, undiscovered planet, no direct observational evidence has been found so far.\n- Voyager 1, launched in 1977, passed the heliopause in 2012 and is now in interstellar space. Its trajectory did not take it near the hypothesized location of Planet X, so it could not have confirmed or ruled out its existence.\n\n### Regarding Nemesis:\n- The **Nemesis hypothesis** suggests that the Sun might have a distant companion star (possibly a red or brown dwarf) that could influence the orbits of outer solar system objects or cause periodic mass extinctions on Earth through gravitational perturbations.\n- There is no evidence from Voyager 1 or any other mission to support the existence of such a star. Modern astronomical surveys have also failed to detect a companion star to the Sun.\n\n### Conclusion:\nVoyager 1 has not been involved in searching for Planet X or Nemesis, and its data does not directly address these hypotheses. The absence of evidence from other missions and surveys suggests that both Planet X and Nemesis remain speculative ideas rather than confirmed realities. However, ongoing astronomical research continues to explore these possibilities.",
